The bells of St. Martin's Episcopal Church in Harlem, New York City, have been silent since 2008. The church is located on 116th Street between Lenox Avenue and Adam Clayton Powell Jr. Boulevard.
The church was founded in 1865 by the Episcopal Diocese of New York. It was named for St. Martin of Tours, a 4th-century Roman soldier who is said to have shared his cloak with a beggar.

English: <s>According to the FWC, patchier bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which suggests decreasing concentrations.</s>
Catalan: <s>According to the FWC, patchier bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which suggests decreasing concentrations.</s>
The Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) has released its weekly report on harmful algal blooms (HABs) in Florida’s coastal waters.
According to the FWC, patchier bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – which suggests decreasing concentrations.
HABs are naturally occurring blooms of microscopic algae that can produce toxins that can be harmful to humans, pets, wildlife, and marine life.
HABs are caused by a variety of factors, including nutrient pollution, freshwater discharges, and wind and wave action.
According to the FWC, patchier bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – which suggests decreasing concentrations.
